segments.text: Student life, and you were talking about Hector and Bill.
Yeah, Bill Mahomes.
What were the major extracurricular student organizations?
MSC.
With whatever it had to do, and that was pretty much it.
Of course, you had intramurals.
We were certainly all involved.
Intramurals were a very important part of campus life.
But it was...
Regular school traditions, sporting activities, things of this nature in NIC.
That was really it.
You weren't not in the Singa Dads.
No.
All right, well, describe the routine of being a yell leader and particularly being a head yell leader.
Oh, it was quite involved back in those days.
I don't know, it was, as head yell leader you were,
horse out front in charge of the Aggie spirit and things of this nature.
But you had a hand in pretty much everything.
Uh, Yelliers were in charge of building the bonfire.
And as head Yellier you had to coordinate all that stuff.
Now then that's left up to committees of folks to do that.
Um, Muster, you were involved in Muster.
You called the name of
of the missing, and you were involved in that program.
Started a school, all-university night.
You were responsible for getting that all organized.
You were pretty much critically involved in everything that took place on campus as Yellier, particularly head Yellier.
You were involved with Student Senate, you were involved with MSC, you were involved with all those activities on the campus.
And I would say that at that point in time, the three positions were core commander, student body president, head yell leader, and probably MSC president, four positions.
And you four were responsible for pretty much everything that happened on campus in some form or fashion.
Can you think of any specific incident, problem, event, et cetera, plus or minus,
that you had to cope with as head yell leader?
You mentioned one, the belt.
The belt, that was the only, that was really the only thing that really stands out in my mind.
I would say that being head yell leader was the most plushable thing that you could just about do at A&M in my opinion.
It is the most high profile position there is.
Everybody, I can tell you all my head yell leaders.
I cannot begin to tell you.
who the student body presidents were.
I think I might can tell you who their core commanders were, but I have to think about that.
But I can darn sure tell you who the head yell leader was.
And he's known by everybody.
Now, what did a head yell leader wear at a football game?
They wore the whites, just like they do now.
The same thing that Lupo gave us.
Oh, I didn't know that.
Oh, yeah.
Lupo contributed to the yellier uniform, and he went over to the

When you got lucky, you'd go over there and you'd find you some of those, they were basically the same uniforms that were used by the dairy employees, but they just put some patches and stuff on them, you know.
And you'd go over there and they'd outfit you with a couple outfits and give them to you.
They were yours.
And they gave you the uniforms and the shoes and the whole bit, and that was it.
Do you remember any
particular games where the weather was extreme.
Oh, yeah.
I remember Florida State my junior year, just the torrential downpour, just unbelievable, rain fog.
Cotton Bowl my junior year, it was so cotton and cold.
And you're freezing to death.
But nothing my senior year, there was anything
weather standpoint or anything else that stands out.
It was pretty much a calm deal.
But the thing about the earlier I tell folks is after I got chosen as head dealer, I must have gotten cuter all of a sudden because my social life just took off.
Girls I couldn't even begin to get to talk to were now calling me.
It was a wonderful social experience at that point in time and a lot of fun.
Describe midnight yell practice to someone who had never known about it.
Well, midnight yell practice is a little different than it is now in that you did gather up in the quad, duck an area, and you took off and you followed the man all through campus.
And we would go off the end of the quad and we'd go through, now it's the library.
The library's there, so you can't do that.
We'd go down there by the chemistry building, turn by the engineering buildings.
We'd come around, pick up by Lysabesa, and come on over by the fish pond, the other dorms in Henderson Hall, and back on around by Simpson Drill Field, MSC, on in to the other.
And we picked up students along the way.
And by the time we got there, we had everybody swaying and arms locked and walking across the campus.
It was a real affair.
Then we got there, and everybody then got into sleep.
Now then,
A few follow the band over and everybody's in the study room ahead of time.
It's not the same in that regard.
Yale practices are a lot larger now than they were then because of the number of people involved.
But they were fun experiences.
They really truly were.
Midnight Yale practice, you'd always have a date and usually had something you were going to beforehand, a dance or a party or something, and midnight Yale and all that

went on there and then the next day of the game it was always a great place these are questions for earlier uh heroes uh going to and from college station you didn't have a car yeah uh you how did you get back and forth and how often
Well, you went back and forth, you'd catch rides with folks from the same part of the country that you were from who might have a car, or you hitchhiked.
And my record was 13 different rides from the campus of A&M to the front door of my parents' farm.
Which I don't want to spend most of the day on those 13 rides to get there.
But most of the times you'd ride with some, you got to know everybody from your part of the country.
And one of the stories I'm told here recently is there was one guy in Atlanta named Danny Barr that I would ride with, and a couple kids from Pittsburgh that I'd ride with, too.
And I remember Danny just didn't ride with him too much because he drove like a mangy gang.
I mean, he would just scare the hell out of me.
What's so funny about all that stuff is that Danny Barr just retired from the Air Force.
For the last, I think, about 10 years of his career, he was a pilot of Air Force One.
And I thought, my God, as a president, how bad a driver he used to be.
But now he's flying the president around in response for his safety.
But I just catch rides with guys going back home.
And it was not a problem.
And we'd go quite often.
When there wasn't something happening on campus, particularly when you're a freshman or sophomore, you want to kind of get out of harm's way.
And that was what you did to do that.
I told, I gave a speech to some of the kids a few years ago.
They wanted to end the semester type of thing.
I wanted to kind of pump them up to come back.

I told them, I said, I think that if I were to ever have an accident and be in a coma, and I could be in a coma for certain months only, and if I would wake up on a Sunday afternoon, I would know it would be a Sunday afternoon.
because I had this sinking feeling in the pit of my stomach that you got on Sunday after you had to go back to the dorm, all on land, because that's exactly right.
That's the same feeling you got.
What were the secrets of Aggie hitchhiking?
You had your little bag that said Texas Aggies on it, this little tote bag, and the uniform helped.
And I never will forget, I was dropped off in Jewett, Texas,
And 79 was one of the main routes back to northeast Texas.
And I was back on the north side of Jewett, and I had my bag down, my uniform in.
Here comes this car with this convertible, two young ladies in it.
And they were blowing down the highway, and I pull on the brakes and think, it's some distance from me.
And I pick my bag, and I run down there.
And I thought, oh, man, my luck has turned.
It's a convertible with two young ladies in it, you know, the whole bit.
And
Just about the time I get there, they take off.
And there were a couple girls from University of Texas.
They made some comment about Aggies and drove off into the sunset.
I remember picking up a rock and wanting to chuck it at them, but I didn't.
Let's see.
You didn't have a car for a while.
No, I did not.
Were there any rules about borrowing cars?
Sure.
The rule was, you put the gas in, you bring it back, and if there's any dents in it, you're responsible for it.
We had two freshmen that had cars when we were freshmen, and we all utilized those cars.
By the time, you know, you got to be juniors and seniors, a lot of the guys had vehicles at that point in time, and you always had an opportunity to get around when they went.
My mother's car, I got to use it.
But as far as my own car, I didn't get one until I was about to graduate, to tell you the truth.
And I really didn't need it.
Didn't need to have a vehicle involved.
I had friends and obviously cars and stuff.
And it was not a problem to get around.
Women were beginning to enroll at A&M.
Describe getting a date, meeting a young lady,
How did a young man accomplish that?
Well, you had to be kind of careful, because the pretty girls most often were married to the guys who were already here on campus.
You had to be careful who you were flirting with, because it might be her husband right behind you.
I think that in my freshman class, I think there were like about 400 girls.
I think we had like about, I don't know, it was like 2,000 or 3,000 folks.
And so that's the girls.
A lot of them were professors, daughters, and things of this nature.
local girls, you did kind of get to know the ones that were single and things of this nature.
And the problem was, as freshmen you didn't get a chance to really get to date them because the upperclassmen did.
And by the time I graduated, the population of the school had risen to like 12,000 and
And there were a lot more girls on campus then.
Still, the main criteria was that most of them were married.
But there were more girls.
But at that point in time, you still had that contact with other schools.
And on weekends, there were just a carload of girls coming in on campus.
Now, where did they stay?
Oh, they would stay at families, homes, or whatever motel facilities that you could find.
in front of mine.
Were there any TASIC visitors?
Oh yeah, there were a lot of girls from TWU would come in.
But primarily at that point in time, it was Baylor girls, Houston girls, TU girls.
You'd find carloads of girls coming in from campuses that, you know, one has a boyfriend and she's bringing four or five other girls.
Dates with his friends, you know, that type of deal.
I've heard about beast buckets and moose pox.
Oh, yeah, I know those things too.
Oh, boy, I was hoping you could understand.
What were the major events, dances, and other social events for which one would hope to have a date?
All the major things that you had, certainly you wanted bonfire.
We had the different balls.
We had the
class balls that you would have.
You'd have a combat ball.
You'd have a military weekend ball.
You had things like junior year, you'd get a big dance.
You had senior, ring dance your senior year.
Those were things you certainly had dates for, plus the football games.
And those big dances were held where?
They were held in the MSC, primarily, or Sabisa.
And how did one dress?
You were in uniform, dress uniform, pretty much always.
As a matter of fact, my wife, I had a date with her from boot dance in my junior year.
That was our first date.
Describe how you happened to meet her.

My brother, you get set up with these sisters, and I had a sister dumped on me a time or two, and I was pretty reluctant to take out sisters because I thought, well, this guy doesn't look any better than he does.
What is a sister going to look like, you know, that type of deal.
I had a friend of mine that was from Northeast Texas also that was classed behind me.
And he came up one day and said, my sister's coming down.
He said, you might like to go out with her.
I said, oh, God, Gary, I've had the sister routine, you know.
He said, no, I got pictures.
And so I went.
I said, I don't want to see them.
So I went.
And she was going to East Texas State at the time.
She was a university beauty and all that kind of stuff up there with all these fraternity sweethearts.
and really involved on her campus.
So I said, sure.
And so we had our date then and didn't follow up.
Well, I can point to it, but she was dating another guy in high school that she'd gone with for a long time.
Anyway, my senior year after football season was over with, I ran into Gary again and asked if his sister was married.
And he says, no, they broke up.
And I said, well.
reintroduce myself, and we ended up getting married about 40 years later.
So, that happened quite often.
You would get set up with blind dates.
Blind dates were old.
That happened quite a bit.
Where were the off-limit places that an A&M student might have gone during that era?
Well, there were certain bars and stuff, particularly in Bryan, that you kind of watched out for.
What were they?
Oh, the Hitchin' Puffs, the Longhorn was another one.
If you wanted your manhood tested, you could get tested pretty quickly if you were so of mind to.
Nezzy's was another one I recall that was kind of one of those places that you might best watch your P's and Q's.
We also had a problem at that point in time with the local kids.
college kids were here in town, and they were the local girls that you would date and things of that nature.
Some of the local high school boys or others took offense at that, and from time to time if you were in an unfavorable situation, you could get jumped.
And I know that that did happen from time to time.
The old KC Ballroom downtown
had a lot of dances and stuff.
If you went with a local girl, you had to be pretty careful.
You might get somebody to try to rearrange your nose for you, stuff like that.
Where did a student go to get alcoholic beverage?
Well, you could get beer from a lot of places around.
But you couldn't.
You had to go across the bridge over to McPherson County, across Whiskey Bridge, it was called.
It's on Highway 60 here.
That was the first liquor store there.
Anybody had to make a liquor run, you had to go to Whiskey Bridge to do that.
It was always a crowded place on Friday afternoons for home football weekends or Saturdays.
As a young Aggie and not being 21, they'd have a lot of beer busts and stuff down the river or whatever that they provide for you.
But we'd, as you'd try to find places, we'd go over to
Snook and Brenham area, because over in those communities, they weren't so particular about age limits.
And kids grew up over there, physical dances and drinking beer.
But I happened to be 21, so we'd go over there.
Alright, if someone went to Whiskey Bridge and brought a bottle back, did they dare take it in the dorm?
No.
Where did it get stored?
It stayed in the trunk of the car until wherever you were going to go and have your party or function or whatever it might be.
That was something that just didn't happen in the dorms.
There wasn't any drinking in the dorms.
It really wasn't.
That was, I saw a lot of people who drunk that came into the dorm, but I really truly can't say that I saw any drinking taking place in the dorms.
Describe the community around the campus, Northgate, Eastgate,
Southgate, what was there?
Well, College Station was not much.
It was a few blocks off of what's now George Bush Drive.
It was that side.
It went a little further on the east side, Walton Drive, back over that area.
The Northgate area was the only business district that there was in town.
What businesses were there?
Oh, you had basically the bookstores and you had
Uh, Waldrop's, which was a men's store.
Uh, you had Mr. Hollick's, a good shop.
Uh, you had Cleaner's.
Uh, you had Charlie's Grocery.
Uh, Lou Ed's Restaurant.
Uh, you had the theater, the campus theater.
Uh, and that was it.
That was the business district.
That fellow that ran that place on the corner that sold a lot of things.
Describe him.
That was a drug store.
That's right.
It was a drug store there.
And Lupo's was down now and basically where the Dixie Chicken is.
Describe Lou.
Oh, curious, outgoing, you know.
Once you saw Lupo, he was always the same.
He did a lot of things for folks.
Of course, he was a businessman, and he was out to get students' involvement in his story and things of this nature.
But he did a lot of things for folks that never knew about it.
And I'll give one story.
Of course, when you're doing this, well, come on back here, good eggs, you know.
And he greeted everybody, good egg, you know.
It was, hey, good egg, how you doing?
Or, hey, fighter.
You know, I don't know.
That was always his greeting to you.
And he always greeted you like he was your long-lost friend, whatever.
And he didn't know you from that end, but that was OK.
I remember one time, one of the guys in the outfit
Younger brother came to campus to visit, and he came in with another friend of his on like a Friday, and his folks were coming in Saturday from the football game.
Well, they ended up in trouble and ended up in jail that night.
And so we're trying to figure out how we can get him out of jail.
We don't have enough money between all of us to get him out of jail.
I can't get him bailed out.
Parents will be here the next day, and brother will say, oh, man, if my folks don't know what just happened, they'll kill me, you know.
I said, we're going to have that money.
Who do we know that has that kind of money?
Lupo's the only one that has that kind of money.
I said, let's call him.
And it was like 2.33 o'clock in the morning.
I call him.
He gets up, puts on his pants, goes down, and tells the kid out of jail.
I thought, now that's great.
That really is.
We paid him back.
No problem with that.
Total stranger.
But he was nagging.
I told him the circumstances.
He said, sir, you bet, son.
I might be doing it.
And he did.
But he was a character.
But he was loved by folks.
He was who he was.
Off-campus events.
What major national or worldwide events do you remember that occurred while you were here as a student?
Oh, I remember all the marches and the riots and things of this nature that took place.
The unrest.
that was existing elsewhere but here.
It was like we were insulating that stuff here.

But this is the peace movement, and I remember the Democratic Convention of 68, that summer, the riots in Chicago, the Black Panthers, all those things that went on and were just timed in our country that I thought, man, where are we going as a nation?
because it was so different than the way Westmont was growing up.
All of a sudden, in about a four year time period there, society changed, big time.
From being segregated, old South, God country, my mouth fired, God country to being something that's hard to recognize.
And it happened very quickly.
It was a very tumultuous time in our country and our lives.
And I saw it in the distance.
I didn't really anticipate that stuff.
What did you and your friends think about Vietnam and its effect on you?
Most of us were, you know, of the opinion, it happens, it happens.
It's something that you're supposed to do.
That sense of duty, I guess.
My family was always
that kind of sense.
My father fought in World War II.
His father fought in World War I. I think if somebody in my family served in every war in our country, they had to serve in the Spanish-American War.
And it was your time and your generation.
You just did it, period.
And so it was, that was kind of the attitude that we had.
And I'll tell you, earlier in my career, people were more gung-ho about the military than they were at the end of it.
At the end of it, you had all these
about what they were really doing.
And of course, you have some hesitancy, too, about the situation.
But I know that most of us did serve, and most of us, a lot of us did feel good.
Was there an impact on dorm and or corps life from Vietnam?
Were there veterans that were on corps staff or in the trigon or anything?
There were some.
We never got into this military peace movement conflict type of deal at all on this campus when I was here.
I know that there were a lot of unrest on the campuses.
The Kent State killing and all the riots that took place.
I think General Rudder had it.
How many demonstrations do you remember here?
Zero.
I was told there was some folks coming over from Austin one time, but they never made it to campus.
The only demonstration, I think, that ever occurred on campus occurred before I got here, and that was in Marsden President's home about the food, quality of the food.
There was nothing like that ever on that campus.
And like I said, we were kind of insulating that stuff in that regard.
And I was kind of glad.
But you'd see it on TV and things of this nature, and you'd say, man.
Let's see.
Student indulgences.
There were some beer and whiskey.
Tobacco?
Yes, tobacco.
And I will just tell you that I never, ever saw the use of any narcotics in any shape or fashion.
Did you even know the words?
No.
I didn't know what all the slang words were.
You know, those are good stuff.
And marijuana, until I got in the military, I did not even know what it looked like, smelled like, or anything else.
I flew this in that regard.
We had kind of a pristine environment here, too, truly.
I never, like I said, I never saw those things until I got off the circus.
Describe a court trip.

Oh, it was helter-skelter, catch as catch can, get there, get there, pile into somebody's home, sleep on the floors, wherever you could, and mom and dad trying everything they could to keep everybody fed and
happy, and it was a great time.
Then the game, March in, and the game and the parties and stuff, it was always a fun trip.
Always a great trip.
I look forward to court trips.
Do you remember any specific high or low point on a court trip?
Oh, I remember a court trip my freshman year before, and we all, whoever lived in that area had to put up with all the classmates.
And we had a couple of guys from the area, so we were able to buy that, buy two or three guys from the area.
And we had a great time, and we go to the game, and we play TCU.
And we're successful.
The game was on the call.
And one thing I remember is we were leaving, and I didn't have dates.
We were just up there with the guys that one time.
And we had a senior, or there was a senior, that got jumped by some pledges from one of the attorneys at TCU.
There were about 20 of those guys there.
He jumped in on his date and tried to take his boots off.
And I recall he started hollering, old army fight.
And so now the chant gets up, old army fight.
And everybody starts talking about, well, next thing you know, we have about 300 of us, and there's about 20 of them.
So the eyes turned about the same way in our favor then.
And they decided being in that fraternity was not, and that task they were given was not what they should be doing, and be the retreat, so to speak.
But that was the thing.
And the others are always fun, too.
We always had a great time.
We enjoyed it.
Our senior year, we took a senior trip as we got to Saline.
And we were on chartered buses and stuff as seniors when we were down there.
We had New Orleans, and it was great.
It was fun.
Describe a typical football day in College Station.
Most of the games were day games.
And so a typical day was that you would
get up and start getting your uniform and stuff together that morning.
You don't go to chow or anything like that, march to chow usually.
But you would have a formation before you go to the game because you would do the marching.
And date, parents and stuff would come to the dorm.
You usually had a mom.
Back in those days, you bought a mom for your date, your mom, whoever.
All the women wore moms.
There were people on the side of the road selling moms to everybody going to the game.
And you would
March over, go to the game.
It was always exciting.
It was always a grand time on campus.
We only had the one level at Kyle Field.
They started building the second level my senior year.
But they didn't have it.
We just had it until the year after I graduated.
So we just had the one level at Kyle Field.
It was always pretty much well attended.
There might be a few seats in the horseshoe sometimes that weren't used.
But most of the time, it was full.
and it was a great moment.
Victory celebrations, what were they?
Well, carrying the Yeliers off the field, carrying the football team off the field.
We didn't have too many of those, so I thought we won one game my freshman year, and that was Gene Stallings' first year.
It was more of a sense of family and closeness and environment
Then I think now the kids on the football team were isolated.
They were part of the campus, and everybody knew them, and they knew a lot of those folks.
A lot more interaction, I thought, between the athletes than there is now.
What was your favorite football game memory?
Victory.
Oh, from a victory standpoint, it would have to be the 10-0 win, like you knew you were going to beat Texas here.
win a conference championship.
Or the second most would be the Texas Tech victory out at Tech, where we had our score with no time left on the block to win that game, which was the start of the run, which was a great deal.

One of the stories I tell about the Tech game is, we're out there with, we had dates with Tech girls and stuff, and we're staying at this apartment with one of his high school buddies who went to Tech.
And we had great girls for a date, pretty girls, and we had a lot of fun.
We go to the game, and they're intrigued by all this Aggie stuff.
It's a great game.
We win the end of the game.
And we're going to go back to the apartment.
We're going to celebrate a little bit.
And I remember walking back.
There was like four of us.
We had our uniforms on.
And we had these dates.
Here comes this freshman.
He was in a uniform, his core uniform.
got one of those bells from those saddle tramps that got him.
And here's about 50 guys in red shirts and black pants just right behind him.
And he's running to beat the thing in.
